2026-07-15 | Maximum Length Bitonic Subarray

	Question
Return the maximum length of a bitonic subarray.
	Key Insight
A bitonic subarray has two parts:
	- Non-decreasing part ending at index `i`.
	- Non-increasing part starting from index `i`.
If we know both lengths for every index, then treating index `i` as the peak gives:
		length =
		inc[i] + dec[i] - 1
The `-1` avoids counting the peak twice.
	DP Arrays
	inc[i]
	= Length of the longest non-decreasing subarray ending at `i`.
	If:
		arr[i] >= arr[i-1]
	then
		inc[i] = inc[i-1] + 1
	else
		inc[i] = 1
	dec[i]
	= Length of the longest non-increasing subarray starting at `i`.
	If:
		arr[i] >= arr[i+1]
	then
		dec[i] = dec[i+1] + 1
	else
		dec[i] = 1
	Finally,
		answer =
		max(inc[i] + dec[i] - 1)
	Approach
1.	Create an array `inc`.
2.	Traverse from left to right to compute the longest non-decreasing subarray ending at every index.
3.	Create an array `dec`.
4.	Traverse from right to left to compute the longest non-increasing subarray starting at every index.
5.	For every index, compute:
			inc[i] + dec[i] - 1
6.	Return the maximum value.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxBitonicSubarray(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        vector<int> inc(n, 1);
        vector<int> dec(n, 1);
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            if(arr[i] >= arr[i - 1])
                inc[i] = inc[i - 1] + 1;
        }
        for(int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            if(arr[i] >= arr[i + 1])
                dec[i] = dec[i + 1] + 1;
        }
        int ans = 1;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans = max(ans, inc[i] + dec[i] - 1);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		arr = [12, 4, 78, 90, 45, 23]
	inc:
		1 1 2 3 1 1
	dec:
		2 1 4 3 2 1
	Maximum:
		at index 3
		3 + 3 - 1 = 5
	Longest bitonic subarray:
		4 78 90 45 23
	Output:
		5
	Key Insight
	Every bitonic subarray has a unique peak. By precomputing the length of the longest **non-decreasing** subarray ending at each index and the longest **non-increasing** subarray starting from each index, we can treat every index as the peak and compute the bitonic length as:
		inc[i] + dec[i] - 1
	This gives an optimal **O(n)** solution.
